<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-05-16T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-05-16T18:00:00-05:00" n="670" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d670">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/4567</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-05-16T18:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 16, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4843. Department is discussing with British Embassy here question
                                presented by British Government, of Liberia declaring war on Germany
                                and transferring German population in Liberia to an Allied country.
                                Embassy was told that before United States could advise Liberia to
                                take this step, this Government would be glad to receive assurance
                                British trading vessels would be permitted to resume their trade
                                with Monrovia. We did not consider it fair to Liberia, which is
                                starving because of prohibition of all trade, that she should be
                                asked to declare war and receive no return.</p>
                            <p>Take matter up with Foreign Office and ask whether trade with
                                Monrovia may be resumed.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>